<!DOCTYPE assessment PUBLIC "-//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Assessment MathML 2.4//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_assessment_mathml_2_4.dtd"><assessment xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/" id="unit3_assessment" recommended_attempts="3" max_attempts="3"><title>Assessment unused</title><page id="c182005d135b4b4badca19bb382d0146"><title>Assessment Page Title</title><multiple_choice id="q1" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="af07f7c38bcab4ba8a304229f0bf09117">Heart rate commonly changes in response to challenges to the body, yet there is no direct sensor for heart rate. This would suggest that heart rate is:</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="c0c239bd225f497cbe71aea32b1e1a41" labels="false"><choice value="A">An input signal</choice><choice value="B">A control center</choice><choice value="C">An effector</choice><choice value="D">None of the above</choice></input><part id="d8dd0273bedd4edd8754984540a14782"><response match="A" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="C" score="10"><feedback /></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback /></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q2" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ac62b8f1fc6be44a9be0bab15e5b9af93">There are multiple sensors for measuring blood pressure. This suggests that:</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="db2920ee94984abc907e72d6d623fb37" labels="false"><choice value="A">There are multiple feedback loops for regulating blood pressure.</choice><choice value="B">The control center integrates information from all sensors.</choice><choice value="C">The body changes which sensor it uses depending on the conditions the body is experiencing.</choice><choice value="D">Both A and B could be correct.</choice></input><part id="c6d5f60be7724540b179c81bcc04ead6"><response match="A" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="D" score="10"><feedback /></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q3" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="df797afc19964062843b8350a78d7332">The control centers for most neural-mediated feedback loops are:</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="ba7bd4fd71754622a257f4e8a122e6d3" labels="false"><choice value="A">In the frontal cortex</choice><choice value="B">In the parietal lobe of the brain</choice><choice value="C">In the brainstem</choice><choice value="D">In the spinal cord</choice></input><part id="e6f1e8cfc1e3417191352daa13e32bfb"><response match="A" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="C" score="10"><feedback /></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback /></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q4" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="af3eee1dc891b46c4aab20c57527b1950">If the pituitary gland is destroyed, how many homeostatic feedback loops would be affected?</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="e48f3fc281b24bafaebd4727eeb21b34" labels="false"><choice value="A">One</choice><choice value="B">Two</choice><choice value="C">Three</choice><choice value="D">More than three</choice></input><part id="a401164564034a799ede454e3cba0d48"><response match="A" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="D" score="10"><feedback /></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q5" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ad986f5147e0c408da09edcdb4bdb64d7">Where is the control center for the regulation of plasma calcium levels in adults?</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="a9e0b57a34264225af7eb83a300c0b54" labels="false"><choice value="A">Thyroid gland</choice><choice value="B">Parathyroid gland</choice><choice value="C">Adrenal gland</choice><choice value="D">Pituitary gland</choice></input><part id="ed86e1d3c36944678a5591f000c4b32f"><response match="A" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="B" score="10"><feedback /></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback /></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q6" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="af1ef70e6bb74439b8e8453e4db57b04f">Which of the following analogies best describes homeostasis?</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="f1e9a01c57a54f33bc5f964a25d42cb6" labels="false"><choice value="A">When you apply the brakes on a car and it slows down.</choice><choice value="B">When you turn the key in the ignition and the car starts.</choice><choice value="C">When cruise control is used to maintain the speed of the car, even on hilly terrain.</choice><choice value="D">When the car burns fuel to produce torque.</choice></input><part id="fa379405f86a4af78d34efa090703b47"><response match="A" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="C" score="10"><feedback /></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback /></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q7" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ae924538f0ed843d38377f8d67077d0db">The main benefit of using negative feedback instead of positive feedback to control a variable is that:</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="ffce85bafb82414f9bc624221c6709b5" labels="false"><choice value="A">Negative feedback can respond more rapidly.</choice><choice value="B">Negative feedback doesnâ€™t require the use of nerves.</choice><choice value="C">Negative feedback brings the variable back toward the set point.</choice><choice value="D">Negative feedback uses a sensor, control center and effector(s).</choice></input><part id="e1eac671cbe843f28fde3c738afbba50"><response match="A" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="C" score="10"><feedback /></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback /></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q8" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ac6314588e1bc434d8fd508db343e8981">In comparison to negative feedback loops, positive feedback loops are more likely to:</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="db385c8734f54f1c83d2e27f27eb25c3" labels="false"><choice value="A">Lead to a disease or a worsened condition.</choice><choice value="B">Respond more quickly.</choice><choice value="C">Use nerves as a mechanism of sending information.</choice><choice value="D">Be utilized to correct for large changes in a variable.</choice></input><part id="ddebcdb69dcf4f14a3f7864fb42f229e"><response match="A" score="10"><feedback /></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback /></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q9" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="ad0c4e6a3437a4779a5b66136aa1d8e3c">An example of positive feedback is:</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="e6996bee77804c5fbd8817c947072e03" labels="false"><choice value="A">The control of plasma glucose.</choice><choice value="B">Maintenance of blood pressure.</choice><choice value="C">The platelet aggregation aspect of hemostasis.</choice><choice value="D">Regulation of plasma osmolarity.</choice></input><part id="fe6a4cd0915e44a7abf38e85706a9e2b"><response match="A" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="C" score="10"><feedback /></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback /></response></part></multiple_choice><multiple_choice id="q10" grading="automatic" select="single"><body><p id="aced63043896545458688adcfcb598c0c">The systems that most often carry information between the components of feedback loops are:</p></body><input shuffle="true" id="e130b205a7524a938bae8a778c460966" labels="false"><choice value="A">Nervous and endocrine</choice><choice value="B">Nervous and circulatory</choice><choice value="C">Endocrine and circulatory</choice><choice value="D">Immune and circulatory</choice></input><part id="fbdce8f7acac4962990153451b9e3e9a"><response match="A" score="10"><feedback /></response><response match="B" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="C" score="0"><feedback /></response><response match="D" score="0"><feedback /></response></part></multiple_choice></page></assessment>
